Analysis of Linked Files: A Missing Data Perspective

Abstract

In many applications, researchers seek to identify overlapping entities across multiple data files. Record linkage algorithms facilitate this task, in the absence of unique identifiers. As these algorithms rely on semi-identifying information, they may miss records that represent the same entity, or incorrectly link records that do not represent the same entity. Analysis of linked files commonly ignores such linkage errors, resulting in biased, or overly precise estimates of the associations of interest. We view record linkage as a missing data problem, and delineate the linkage mechanisms that underpin analysis methods with linked files. Following the missing data literature, we group these methods under three categories: likelihood and Bayesian methods, imputation methods, and weighting methods. We summarize the assumptions and limitations of the methods, and evaluate their performance in a wide range of simulation scenarios.

1 Introduction

In many healthcare and social science applications, information about entities is dispersed across multiple data files. To investigate the associations of interest, researchers seek to link records representing the same entity across these files. When unique identifiers, like social security numbers, are available, linking records is a relatively straightforward task. However, privacy regulations often limit access to such identifiers. In these situations, researchers rely on semi-identifying linking variables, such as names and addresses. Record linkage (data matching or entity resolution) is a statistical technique that identifies records representing the same entity across multiple files, in the absence of unique identifiers. Record linkage techniques have found applications in epidemiology and healthcare (Stern,, 1986; Brenner et al.,, 1997; Golden and Mirel,, 2021), official statistics (Winkler and Thibaudeau,, 1991; Dasylva et al.,, 2014), economics (Meyer and Mittag,, 2019, 2021), and studies of human rights violations (Sadinle,, 2014).

Record linkage methods can be broadly categorized as being deterministic or probabilistic. Deterministic linkage methods are based on non-random similarity functions defined on the linking variables. These methods can link records with high accuracy, when the linking variables are informative and accurately reported (Gomatam et al.,, 2002). However, when these variables are subject to variations in spelling, data entry errors, or incompleteness, deterministic methods may perform inadequately (Campbell et al.,, 2008; Newman et al.,, 2009; Zhu et al.,, 2015). Probabilistic linkage is based on the likelihood that a given pair of records represents the same entity. This likelihood can be computed in several ways, such as using mixture models (Fellegi and Sunter,, 1969), microclustering models (Zanella et al.,, 2016), or classification algorithms (Cochinwala et al.,, 2001).

A widely-used approach to probabilistic record linkage is the mixture model proposed by Fellegi and Sunter, (1969). For computational convenience, this model relies on several tacit independence assumptions. In addition, identification of linked records is based on subjective thresholds (Winkler,, 2014; Binette and Steorts,, 2022). These features have often been criticized (Tancredi and Liseo,, 2011), motivating the development of parametric Bayesian approaches for probabilistic linkage (Tancredi and Liseo,, 2011; Gutman et al.,, 2013; Steorts et al.,, 2016; Sadinle,, 2017).

Probabilistic record linkage has also been viewed as a prediction problem (Lee et al.,, 2022). In this approach, classification algorithms, like decision trees, are used to determine if a pair of records represents the same entity (Cochinwala et al.,, 2001; Bilenko and Mooney,, 2003). Such algorithms rely on the availability of training data, i.e., a known set of links, to estimate parameters in the classification algorithm. These estimates are then used to predict the unknown linkage status of record pairs. In the absence of training data, unsupervised classification algorithms, such as k𝑘k-means clustering, can be employed to link records (Liu et al.,, 2003; Gu and Baxter,, 2006; Christen,, 2007; Christen, 2008a, ; Christen, 2008b, ). The performance of both supervised and unsupervised classification algorithms can depend on the distance functions used to compare the records (Asher et al.,, 2020). When reliable training data is available, supervised algorithms can outperform unsupervised algorithms in terms of linkage accuracy (Elfeky et al.,, 2003; Liu et al.,, 2003).

In this article, we exclusively focus on probabilistic record linkage when no training data is available. We also do not focus on predictive classification approaches to probabilistic linking, which have been comprehensively reviewed in Binette and Steorts, (2022).

When the linking variables contain limited information, probabilistic linking algorithms may miss links between records representing the same entity, or falsely link records representing different entities. When analyzing linked files, such errors can lead to substantial biases and a loss in efficiency (Neter et al.,, 1965). In this article, we review statistical methods to propagate the uncertainty stemming from linkage errors into the post-linkage analysis. We do so by formulating record linkage within a missing data framework (Rubin,, 1976), and formalizing linkage mechanisms that underlie inferential methods with linked files. In addition, we characterize and compare the performance of selected linkage and inference methods under a wide variety of scenarios.

This article is organized as follows. The remainder of Section 1 provides notation and background on probabilistic record linkage. Sections 2 and 3 identify and discuss inferential methods with linked files. Section 4 describes simulations to compare the performance of selected methods from Sections 2 and 3. Section 5 concludes with a discussion.

1.1.2 The Fellegi-Sunter model

Each record pair is classified as a link, non-link, or a possible link, by comparing w^i​jsubscript^𝑤𝑖𝑗\hat{w}_{ij} to two fixed thresholds (Tepping,, 1968; Binette and Steorts,, 2022). Choosing optimal thresholds is a subjective process, based on manual review of record pairs (Dusetzina et al.,, 2014), or on the evaluation of linkage quality measures at different threshold values (Christen and Goiser,, 2005, 2007).

The original FS model classifies the linkage status of each record pair independently, often resulting in many-to-one links. Jaro, (1989) addressed this, by introducing a linear sum optimization as a precursor to the FS model.

Multiple extensions to the FS model have been proposed. These include incorporating information from clerical reviews (Larsen and Rubin,, 2001), modeling the dependence between linking variables (Winkler,, 1993; Schürle,, 2005; Xu et al.,, 2019), handling continuous-valued linking variables (Vo et al.,, 2023), handling missing data (Li et al.,, 2022; Sadinle,, 2017), testing the conditional independence assumption (Xu et al.,, 2022), improved scalability (Enamorado et al.,, 2019), and extensions to multi-file linkage (Sadinle and Fienberg,, 2013; Aleshin-Guendel and Sadinle,, 2022; Taylor et al.,, 2024).

1.1.3 Linkage errors

Given that probabilistic linkage relies on semi-identifying information, the estimated 𝚫𝚫\mathbf{\Delta} is seldom error-free. In particular, a linked file may contain two kinds of linkage errors: (i) false links between records representing different entities; and (ii) false non-links between records representing the same entity.

False links can lead to erroneous estimates of the associations of interest (Neter et al.,, 1965). For instance, in linear regression models, false links can induce attenuation bias when estimating the regression coefficients (Wang et al.,, 2022; Patki and Shapiro,, 2023). False links can also have implications when estimating causal effects (Wortman and Reiter,, 2018), mortality rates (Krewski et al.,, 2005), and population sizes (Isaki and Schultz,, 1987; Di Consiglio and Tuoto,, 2015, 2018). False non-links reduce the number of records available for analysis, leading to a loss in statistical power and increased variability in estimates (Haas et al.,, 1994; Harron et al.,, 2017). False non-links can also induce selection bias in the post-linkage inferences. Selection bias occurs when particular groups of records are less likely to link, and are thus excluded from the analysis (Lariscy,, 2011; Bohensky,, 2015; Reiter,, 2021).

The extent of errors in a linked file is determined by the degree of information contained in the linking variables. This information can be summarized in terms of two metrics: the reliability and the discriminatory power (Shlomo,, 2019).

The reliability is the probability that a linking variable is similar, given that a record pair is a link. Reliability reflects the quality of the linking variable, and is diminished when there is measurement error or missingness. For records i∈𝐀𝑖𝐀i\in\mathbf{A} and j∈𝐁𝑗𝐁j\in\mathbf{B}, the aggregate reliability across all linking variables is quantified by m​(γi​j)𝑚subscript𝛾𝑖𝑗m(\gamma_{ij}) (Shlomo,, 2019). Low reliability of the linking variables is typically associated with a higher proportion of false non-links (Tromp et al.,, 2006, 2011). The discriminatory power is the probability that a linking variable is similar, given that a record pair is a non-link (Doidge and Harron,, 2018). The theoretical number of possible values of the linking variable, and their empirical distribution, determines this probability. The combined discriminatory power of all linking variables is quantified by u​(γi​j)𝑢subscript𝛾𝑖𝑗u(\gamma_{ij}) (Shlomo,, 2019). If the combined discriminatory power is low, the record linkage algorithm may identify a high proportion of false links (Tromp et al.,, 2006, 2011).

Both these metrics have been used to assess the feasibility and performance of the FS model (Roos et al.,, 1992; Cook et al.,, 2001). Modifications to the FS weights based on the discriminatory power have also been proposed (Yancey,, 2000; Winkler,, 2000; Zhu et al.,, 2009; Xu et al.,, 2021; Vo et al.,, 2023).

1.1.4 Blocking

With large file sizes, comparing all record pairs across the two files becomes computationally cumbersome. Large files also prompt a higher chance of occurrence of linkage errors (Wang et al.,, 2022). To improve the scalability and accuracy of the linkage process, deterministic blocking is a commonly implemented pre-processing technique. In this technique, only those records that agree on predefined, highly accurate blocking variables are compared. Records that do not agree on these variables are considered non-links.

When utilizing deterministic blocking, it is important to ascertain an optimal block size, which often involves a cost-benefit trade-off (Baxter and Christen,, 2003). Large blocks generate a correspondingly large record comparison space, and may not provide substantial gains in computational efficiency or accuracy. When the blocks are too small, the record linking algorithm may miss many true links (Baxter and Christen,, 2003). Methods that utilize training data to determine optimum blocking schemes have been proposed as possible solutions (Bilenko et al.,, 2006; Michelson and Knoblock,, 2006; Campbell et al.,, 2021).

When blocking variables are error-prone, records may be placed in the wrong block, leading to linkage errors. Possible solutions include using multiple blocking passes (Baxter and Christen,, 2003), complex indexing schemes (Murray,, 2015), or a combination of deterministic and data-driven blocking (McVeigh et al.,, 2020). Other alternatives include probabilistic blocking, which simultaneously infers the blocking scheme and the linkage parameters (Steorts et al., 2014a, ). Probabilistic blocking can effectively propagate blocking uncertainty into the downstream statistical analysis (Marchant et al.,, 2021).

When files are partitioned into deterministic blocks, typical practice is to implement the linkage algorithm independently within each block (Tancredi and Liseo,, 2011; Murray,, 2015; Sadinle,, 2017). However, it is also possible to allow the linkage algorithm to borrow information across blocks (Gutman et al.,, 2013; Shan et al.,, 2022).

1.2.1 A taxonomy of linkage mechanisms

A linkage mechanism characterizes the relationship between the linkage structure and the variables in the individual files. There are broad parallels between missing data mechanisms (Rubin,, 1976), and linkage mechanisms. For a given prior on 𝚫𝚫\boldsymbol{\Delta}, we define four mechanisms that describe f​(𝚫|𝐋A,𝐋B,𝐘A,𝐗B,𝜽)𝑓conditional𝚫subscript𝐋𝐴subscript𝐋𝐵subscript𝐘𝐴subscript𝐗𝐵𝜽f(\boldsymbol{\Delta}|\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B},\mathbf{Y}_{A},\mathbf{X}_{B},\boldsymbol{\theta}), where 𝜽𝜽\boldsymbol{\theta} is a vector parameter governing the distribution. A more restrictive version of SNL states that the linkage is completely independent of 𝐋A,𝐋B,𝐘A,𝐗Bsubscript𝐋𝐴subscript𝐋𝐵subscript𝐘𝐴subscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B},\mathbf{Y}_{A},\mathbf{X}_{B}. Thus, f​(𝚫|𝐋A,𝐋B,𝐘A,𝐗B,𝜽)=f​(𝚫|𝜽)𝑓conditional𝚫subscript𝐋𝐴subscript𝐋𝐵subscript𝐘𝐴subscript𝐗𝐵𝜽𝑓conditional𝚫𝜽f(\boldsymbol{\Delta}|\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B},\mathbf{Y}_{A},\mathbf{X}_{B},\boldsymbol{\theta})=f(\boldsymbol{\Delta}|\boldsymbol{\theta}) for all 𝐋A,𝐋B,𝐘Asubscript𝐋𝐴subscript𝐋𝐵subscript𝐘𝐴\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B},\mathbf{Y}_{A}, 𝐗B,subscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{X}_{B}, and 𝜽𝜽\boldsymbol{\theta}. Han and Lahiri, (2019) refer to this as linkage completely at random (LCAR), similar to when the data are missing completely at random (MCAR) (Rubin,, 1976). A special case of the LCAR mechanism is when f​(𝚫|𝜽)𝑓conditional𝚫𝜽f(\boldsymbol{\Delta}|\boldsymbol{\theta}) is a constant. To exemplify an NL scenario, suppose that file 𝐁𝐁\mathbf{B} contains the covariate age, and file 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A} is a subset of units in file 𝐁𝐁\mathbf{B} that are less than 60 years old. While age is not a linking variable common to both files, it implicitly informs the linkage. The NL mechanism is also a special case of the MAR mechanism, where auxiliary variables 𝐋Asubscript𝐋𝐴\mathbf{L}_{A} and 𝐋Bsubscript𝐋𝐵\mathbf{L}_{B}, and substantively important variables 𝐗Bsubscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{X}_{B}, inform the linkage.

Definition 1.3.

Weakly non-informative linkage (WNL): The linkage mechanism is said to be weakly non-informative, if f​(𝚫|𝐋A,𝐋B,𝐘A,𝐗B,𝜽)𝑓conditional𝚫subscript𝐋𝐴subscript𝐋𝐵subscript𝐘𝐴subscript𝐗𝐵𝜽f(\boldsymbol{\Delta}|\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B},\mathbf{Y}_{A},\mathbf{X}_{B},\boldsymbol{\theta}) depends on 𝐋A,𝐋B,𝐘A, and ​𝐗Bsubscript𝐋𝐴subscript𝐋𝐵subscript𝐘𝐴 and subscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B},\mathbf{Y}_{A},\text{ and }\mathbf{X}_{B}, for all 𝜽𝜽\boldsymbol{\theta}.

The WNL mechanism is also comparable to the MAR mechanism, as only fully observed variables inform the linkage.

Definition 1.4.

Informative linkage (IL): The linkage mechanism is said to be informative, if none of the above linkage mechanisms hold. For instance, the conditional distribution of 𝚫𝚫\boldsymbol{\Delta} may depend on extraneous variables not observed in either file.

IL may induce bias in the post-linkage inferences, particularly if such extraneous variables are associated with the substantively important variables. The IL mechanism is comparable to the missing not at random (MNAR) mechanism (Rubin,, 1976), as the linkage status depends on unobserved quantities.

In what follows, we discuss linked-data inferential methods that rely on one or more of the linkage mechanisms as their underlying assumptions.

2 Primary analysis of linked files

Primary analysis refers to the situation when the record linkage and the post-linkage analysis are performed by the same individual. Alternatively, the analyst has access to files 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A} and 𝐁𝐁\mathbf{B}, or to the likelihood of every record pair (i∈𝐀,j∈𝐁)formulae-sequence𝑖𝐀𝑗𝐁(i\in\mathbf{A},j\in\mathbf{B}) being a link. Following the missing data literature (Molenberghs et al.,, 2014; Little and Rubin,, 2019), we classify primary analysis methods into three broad categories: likelihood and Bayesian methods, imputation methods, and weighting methods. We note that this classification can be overlapping. For instance, some methods can be classified as being both Bayesian and imputation-based, as proper MI methods commonly rely on sampling from (approximate) Bayesian posterior distributions (Rubin,, 1996).

The direct modeling approach for 𝒫​(𝚫|𝐋A,𝐋B)𝒫conditional𝚫subscript𝐋𝐴subscript𝐋𝐵\mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\Delta}|\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B}) assumes that the linking variables 𝐋Asubscript𝐋𝐴\mathbf{L}_{A} and 𝐋Bsubscript𝐋𝐵\mathbf{L}_{B} are erroneous versions of their true latent values. Under the assumption of bipartite linkage, Tancredi and Liseo, (2011) utilize a hierarchical generative model to specify ℒl​(𝐋A,𝐋B|𝚫)subscriptℒ𝑙subscript𝐋𝐴conditionalsubscript𝐋𝐵𝚫\mathcal{L}_{l}(\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B}|\boldsymbol{\Delta}). This is a mixture distribution with two components: a point mass at the true values of 𝐋A​isubscript𝐋𝐴𝑖\mathbf{L}_{Ai} or 𝐋B​jsubscript𝐋𝐵𝑗\mathbf{L}_{Bj}, and a uniform distribution over the remaining points in the support of 𝜼𝜼\boldsymbol{\eta}. At the top level of the hierarchy, a distribution for 𝜼Asubscript𝜼𝐴\boldsymbol{\eta}_{A} and 𝜼Bsubscript𝜼𝐵\boldsymbol{\eta}_{B} given 𝚫𝚫\boldsymbol{\Delta} is postulated. The number of links nA​B=∑i∑jΔi​jsubscript𝑛𝐴𝐵subscript𝑖subscript𝑗subscriptΔ𝑖𝑗n_{AB}=\sum_{i}\sum_{j}\Delta_{ij} is treated as a random quantity. Under diffuse prior distributions on nA​Bsubscript𝑛𝐴𝐵n_{AB} and 𝚫𝚫\boldsymbol{\Delta}, the joint posterior distribution is explored via Metropolis-within-Gibbs algorithms (Robert and Casella,, 1999).

Steorts et al., (2016) build on the measurement error model of Hall and Fienberg, (2012), and posit a likelihood for a bipartite graph that maps every record to a latent population entity. Akin to Tancredi and Liseo, (2011), the likelihood postulates that the linking variables are noisy representations of latent, multinomial random variables. The prior distribution on the linkage structure is assumed to be uniform, and posterior sampling is accomplished via Metropolis-within-Gibbs algorithms with split-merge proposal moves (Steorts et al., 2014b, ). Linking records to latent entities, rather than to other records, allows the model to handle linkage of multiple files, and duplicates within a file.

The original methodologies of Tancredi and Liseo, (2011) and Steorts et al., (2016) are restricted to categorical linking variables. Extensions to incorporate multivariate normal linking variables (Liseo and Tancredi,, 2011), and string-valued linking variables (Steorts,, 2015) have also been proposed.

In some applications, it may be difficult to directly model complex linking variables, like addresses or telephone numbers. A solution is to define the likelihood ℒl​(𝐋A,𝐋B|𝚫)subscriptℒ𝑙subscript𝐋𝐴conditionalsubscript𝐋𝐵𝚫\mathcal{L}_{l}(\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B}|\boldsymbol{\Delta}) using comparison vectors γi​jsubscript𝛾𝑖𝑗\gamma_{ij} (Section 1.1.2). Akin to the FS model, the comparison vectors are assumed to follow a mixture distribution over the set of links and non-links. However, bipartite linkage is explicitly enforced via a prior distribution on 𝚫𝚫\boldsymbol{\Delta}. This approach was developed by Fortini et al., (2001) and Larsen, (2002, 2005) for the case of binary comparison vectors. Sadinle, (2017) extended it to include partial agreements on complex linking variables, and to accommodate ignorable missingness (Rubin,, 1976) in the linking variables. Formally, the model is

2.1.2 Likelihood and Bayesian inference under WNL

The linkage averaging approach in Equation (6) can propagate linkage uncertainty to the downstream analysis. However, information from the analysis models is not utilized in the linkage process. An alternative is to allow the analysis models to inform the linkage. In a Bayesian framework, this can be accomplished by sampling 𝚫𝚫\boldsymbol{\Delta} and 𝜷𝜷\boldsymbol{\beta} simultaneously from their joint posterior distribution (Equation (5)).

It has been shown analytically, and via simulations, that incorporating substantive relationships into the linkage process can facilitate correct identification of links and non-links (Kamat et al.,, 2023). These improvements are commonly called the “feedback effect” of the post-linkage analysis model (Steorts et al.,, 2018). The magnitude of the improvements can depend on (i) fit of the specified likelihood ℒa​(𝐘A,𝐗B|𝐋A,𝐋B,𝚫,𝜷)subscriptℒ𝑎subscript𝐘𝐴conditionalsubscript𝐗𝐵subscript𝐋𝐴subscript𝐋𝐵𝚫𝜷\mathcal{L}_{a}(\mathbf{Y}_{A},\mathbf{X}_{B}|\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B},\boldsymbol{\Delta},\boldsymbol{\beta}); and (ii) the strength of the association between 𝐘Asubscript𝐘𝐴\mathbf{Y}_{A} and 𝐗Bsubscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{X}_{B}.

Sampling from the joint posterior distribution in Equation (5) can be accomplished via the DA algorithm. At the mt​hsuperscript𝑚𝑡ℎm^{th} iteration, this algorithm iterates between two steps: (i) I-Step: Impute 𝚫(m)superscript𝚫𝑚\boldsymbol{\Delta}^{(m)} from the posterior full conditional distribution 𝒫​(𝚫|𝐋A,𝐋B,𝐘A,𝐗B,𝜷(m−1))𝒫conditional𝚫subscript𝐋𝐴subscript𝐋𝐵subscript𝐘𝐴subscript𝐗𝐵superscript𝜷𝑚1\mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\Delta}|\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B},\mathbf{Y}_{A},\mathbf{X}_{B},\boldsymbol{\beta}^{(m-1)}); and (ii) P-step: Sample 𝜷(m)superscript𝜷𝑚\boldsymbol{\beta}^{(m)} from the posterior full conditional distribution 𝒫​(𝜷|𝐋A,𝐋B,𝐘A,𝐗B,𝚫(m))𝒫conditional𝜷subscript𝐋𝐴subscript𝐋𝐵subscript𝐘𝐴subscript𝐗𝐵superscript𝚫𝑚\mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\beta}|\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B},\mathbf{Y}_{A},\mathbf{X}_{B},\boldsymbol{\Delta}^{(m)}). The resultant samples of 𝜷𝜷\boldsymbol{\beta} incorporate the uncertainty around 𝚫𝚫\boldsymbol{\Delta}, and can be used for point and interval estimation.

Gutman et al., (2013) model the associations between variables common to both files, and those exclusive to either file. High quality linking variables are utilized in an informative blocking step, which reduces the computational complexity. Within each block, the linkage is assumed to be bipartite and complete, so that every record in the smaller block can be linked to a unique record in the larger block. The linkage likelihood ℒl​(𝐋A,𝐋B|𝚫)subscriptℒ𝑙subscript𝐋𝐴conditionalsubscript𝐋𝐵𝚫\mathcal{L}_{l}(\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B}|\boldsymbol{\Delta}) is defined using a joint distribution that describes inconsistently recorded linking variables. The distributional form of ℒa​(𝐘A,𝐗B|𝐋A,𝐋B,𝚫,𝜷)subscriptℒ𝑎subscript𝐘𝐴conditionalsubscript𝐗𝐵subscript𝐋𝐴subscript𝐋𝐵𝚫𝜷\mathcal{L}_{a}(\mathbf{Y}_{A},\mathbf{X}_{B}|\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B},\boldsymbol{\Delta},\boldsymbol{\beta}) is specific to the application, and can include models of scientific interest, and models for relationships that only inform the linkage. For unlinked records in the larger block, variables in the smaller block are treated as missing data, and imputed as part of an overarching DA scheme. Under a uniform prior on 𝚫𝚫\boldsymbol{\Delta}, posterior sampling for 𝚫𝚫\boldsymbol{\Delta} is accomplished via Metropolis algorithms. Dalzell and Reiter, (2018) extend the model of Gutman et al., (2013) to incorporate erroneous blocking variables, and to allow individual records to shift between blocks.

A limitation of the approach of Gutman et al., (2013) is the assumption of complete linkage, which can be violated in practice. An alternative approach augments the Bayesian FS likelihood (Equation (8)) with relationships between variables exclusive to either file (Tang et al.,, 2020; Kamat et al.,, 2023). Bayesian generative models have also been applied in a joint modeling framework, in the context of linear regression (Tancredi and Liseo,, 2015; Steorts et al.,, 2018), and small area estimation (Briscolini et al.,, 2018).

Hof and Zwinderman, (2014) propose to estimate 𝜷𝜷\boldsymbol{\beta} by maximizing the complete-data likelihood ℒcsubscriptℒ𝑐\mathcal{L}_{c}, over all possible values of 𝚫𝚫\boldsymbol{\Delta}. Since the parameter space of 𝚫𝚫\boldsymbol{\Delta} is fairly large, maximizing ℒcsubscriptℒ𝑐\mathcal{L}_{c} can be computationally prohibitive. As a solution, Hof and Zwinderman, (2014) propose a two-step pseudo-likelihood approach to estimate 𝜷𝜷\boldsymbol{\beta}. In the first step, estimates of the linking probabilities for all record pairs are computed under the FS model. These estimates are treated as fixed constants in the pseudo-likelihood. In the second step, the pseudo-likelihood is maximized using the EM algorithm, to obtain an estimate 𝜷^bold-^𝜷\boldsymbol{\hat{\beta}}. The sampling variance of 𝜷^bold-^𝜷\boldsymbol{\hat{\beta}}, and confidence intervals for 𝜷𝜷\boldsymbol{\beta}, can be computed using the Bootstrap, or an asymptotic normal approximation for the sampling distribution of 𝜷^bold-^𝜷\boldsymbol{\hat{\beta}}. A similar inferential approach for time-to-event data has been proposed in Hof et al., (2017).

2.2 Imputation

Fully Bayesian approaches to estimating 𝜷𝜷\boldsymbol{\beta} can propagate linkage uncertainty in a principled manner, but are computationally intensive. Moreover, in a joint modeling framework, the models used in the linkage, namely ℒa​(𝐘A,𝐗B|𝐋A,𝐋B,𝚫,𝜷)subscriptℒ𝑎subscript𝐘𝐴conditionalsubscript𝐗𝐵subscript𝐋𝐴subscript𝐋𝐵𝚫𝜷\mathcal{L}_{a}(\mathbf{Y}_{A},\mathbf{X}_{B}|\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B},\boldsymbol{\Delta},\boldsymbol{\beta}), may differ from the scientific model of interest. In such situations, an alternative is to approximate a fully Bayesian analysis using multiple imputation (MI) (Rubin,, 1987).

In MI, M>1𝑀1M>1 imputations of the linkage structure are generated from its posterior distribution. Each imputation is analyzed separately, and estimates are pooled across the imputations using common combination rules (Rubin,, 1987; Little and Rubin,, 2019). This procedure can propagate linkage uncertainty into the downstream analysis, while simplifying the computation. Application of MI to linked-data inference has been exemplified in Gutman et al., (2013), Abowd et al., (2021), and Shan et al., (2021), among others.

Formally, in each of the M𝑀M posterior samples of the linkage structure, 𝚫(1),…,𝚫(M)superscript𝚫1…superscript𝚫𝑀\boldsymbol{\Delta}^{(1)},\dots,\boldsymbol{\Delta}^{(M)}, we obtain a point estimate, 𝜷^(m)superscriptbold-^𝜷𝑚\boldsymbol{\hat{\beta}}^{(m)}, and its sampling variance U(m)superscript𝑈𝑚U^{(m)}, for m=1,…,M𝑚1…𝑀m=1,\dots,M. A limitation of MI is that the imputation model for 𝚫𝚫\boldsymbol{\Delta} may be uncongenial (Meng,, 1994; Xie and Meng,, 2017) to the post-linkage analysis model. The analysis model is congenial to the imputation model, if there exists a unifying Bayesian model for the complete data that embeds both of them (Murray,, 2018). An uncongenial imputation model may lead to biased point estimates, and interval estimates with invalid coverages (van Buuren,, 2018). Since congeniality is hard to ascertain in practice, a general solution is to use an imputation model that is less restrictive than the analysis model. Thus, it may be advisable to include as many relationships of substantive interest as possible in the imputation model for 𝚫𝚫\boldsymbol{\Delta} (Rubin,, 1996; Xie and Meng,, 2017). The joint modeling approaches in Section 2.1.2 can provide a way to accomplish this.

Goldstein et al., (2012) propose to cast linking two files in a statistical matching framework (D’Orazio et al.,, 2006). One limitation of the algorithm is that a set of known links is required to estimate the parameters in pB|A​(𝐗B|𝐘A,𝐋A,𝐋B)subscript𝑝conditional𝐵𝐴conditionalsubscript𝐗𝐵subscript𝐘𝐴subscript𝐋𝐴subscript𝐋𝐵p_{B|A}(\mathbf{X}_{B}|\mathbf{Y}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{A},\mathbf{L}_{B}). This is equivalent to 𝐗Bsubscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{X}_{B} being missing at random (Goldstein et al.,, 2012). Violation of this assumption can lead to substantial bias in point estimates (Harron et al.,, 2014). A possible mitigation strategy is to make the MAR assumption more plausible, by specifying rich imputation models that accommodate variables from auxiliary data sources (Goldstein and Harron,, 2015).

2.3 Weighting

Weighting methods aim to obtain unbiased parameter estimates of generalized linear models fit with linked data. These methods are confined to scenarios where a univariate response 𝐘Asubscript𝐘𝐴\mathbf{Y}_{A} is regressed on a set of covariates 𝐗Bsubscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{X}_{B}. Weighting methods rely on two assumptions. The first assumption is that the linkage is complete, i.e., the smaller file 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A} is a subset of the larger file 𝐁𝐁\mathbf{B}, so that nA​B=nAsubscript𝑛𝐴𝐵subscript𝑛𝐴n_{AB}=n_{A}. The point estimator 𝜷^L​Lsuperscript^𝜷𝐿𝐿\hat{{\boldsymbol{\beta}}}^{LL} is unbiased when 𝐐𝐐\mathbf{Q} is known. However, in most applications, only an estimate of 𝐐𝐐\mathbf{Q} is available. When 𝐐𝐐{\mathbf{Q}} is estimated using the FS model, its rows may not sum to one, as the one-to-one linkage constraint is not enforced. A possible solution is to normalize each entry in 𝐐𝐐\mathbf{Q} as qi​j′=qi​j/∑j∈𝐁qi​jsubscriptsuperscript𝑞′𝑖𝑗subscript𝑞𝑖𝑗subscript𝑗𝐁subscript𝑞𝑖𝑗q^{{}^{\prime}}_{ij}=q_{ij}/\sum_{j\in\mathbf{B}}q_{ij}.

This limitation can be overcome by estimating 𝐐𝐐\mathbf{Q} using a bootstrap for the entire linkage process (Winglee et al.,, 2005; Chipperfield and Chambers,, 2015). Other variations of the weighting approach have been proposed, including using weighted least squares when covariates are spread over multiple files (Hof and Zwinderman,, 2012), and relaxing the assumption of complete linkage (Hof and Zwinderman,, 2012; Chipperfield and Chambers,, 2015).

Computation of variances with estimated weights is generally not straightforward (Little and Rubin,, 2019). Valid variance estimators require elaborate theoretical calculations (Tsiatis,, 2006), or computationally-intensive resampling techniques (Little and Rubin,, 2019). For particular choices of υ​(𝐗B;𝜷)𝜐subscript𝐗𝐵𝜷\upsilon(\mathbf{X}_{B};\boldsymbol{\beta}), Han, (2018) derives theoretical plug-in estimators for the sampling variance of 𝜷^^𝜷\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} under Equation (12). To simplify calculations, Han, (2018) suggests truncating every row of 𝐐𝐐\mathbf{Q} to include the highest (or two highest) values. These estimators, however, do not account for the uncertainty arising from using an estimate of 𝐐𝐐\mathbf{Q}. This can be addressed by using resampling methods that re-estimate 𝐐𝐐\mathbf{Q} at every iteration. Two such methods are based on the unified Jackknife theory (Jiang et al.,, 2002; Han and Lahiri,, 2019), and the Bootstrap (Lahiri and Larsen,, 2005).

2.4 Interlude: Estimating complex models with linked files

A majority of the linked-data inferential methods in the literature center around estimating parameters of generalized linear models. Some work has also focused on inferring the size of a closed population, using capture-recapture (Fienberg,, 1972) or multiple-systems estimation (Bird and King,, 2018). For example, Bayesian models for concurrently inferring the linkage and the population size have been developed, for the case of two files (Tancredi and Liseo,, 2011), and multiple files (Tancredi et al.,, 2020).

The Bayesian and imputation-based approaches also offer a flexible framework to estimate other complex models, such as hierarchical models (Gelman et al.,, 2013), or multivariate analyses like finite mixture models (Peel and MachLachlan,, 2000). As some multivariate analysis methods are exploratory in nature (for e.g, factor analysis), posterior sampling within a fully Bayesian framework can be computationally daunting (Conti et al.,, 2014). In such cases, an MI approach can offer more feasibility. In Section 4.2, we provide an example of using MI to perform model-based cluster analysis with a linked file.

3 Secondary analysis of linked files

Secondary analysis refers to settings when the linkage and the data analysis are performed by different individuals. Specifically, the data analyst is provided a linked file, but does not have access to the individual files, the linking variables, or linking probabilities for record pairs. This situation arises when the original data comprise sensitive information, and releasing individual files interferes with privacy regulations, or poses considerable disclosure risks (Gilbert et al.,, 2017; Christen et al.,, 2020).

In secondary analysis, the analyst does not have access to records that were left unlinked during the linkage process. Consequently, most analysis methods can only propagate the uncertainty due to false links. Inferences from the linked file may not be generalizable to the entire population of entities, without assumptions on the relationship between the linked and unlinked records, or availability of additional information about the unlinked records.

Formally, secondary analysis is based on the file 𝐅≡{𝐘A​l,𝐗B​l}l=1nA​B𝐅superscriptsubscriptsubscript𝐘𝐴𝑙subscript𝐗𝐵𝑙𝑙1subscript𝑛𝐴𝐵\mathbf{F}\equiv\{\mathbf{Y}_{Al},\mathbf{X}_{Bl}\}_{l=1}^{n_{AB}}, obtained by linking files 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A} and 𝐁𝐁\mathbf{B}. The file 𝐅𝐅\mathbf{F} can be partitioned into true and false links, but this partitioning is unknown. In this case, we reformulate the linkage structure using a vector of indicators 𝐂={Cl}𝐂subscript𝐶𝑙\mathbf{C}=\{C_{l}\}, where Cl=1subscript𝐶𝑙1C_{l}=1 if record pair l𝑙l is a true link, and Cl=0subscript𝐶𝑙0C_{l}=0, otherwise, where l=1,…​nA​B𝑙1…subscript𝑛𝐴𝐵l=1,\dots n_{AB}.

3.2 Weighting

In a secondary analysis setting, the matrix 𝐐𝐐\mathbf{Q} (Equation (9)) can only be modeled using coarse summary statistics from the linkage process. One such statistic is the overall proportion of correct links, λ𝜆\lambda. This can be calculated, for example, by comparing a representative audit sample from the linked file to a gold-standard linked file (Chambers and Diniz da Silva,, 2020).

Under the assumption that nA=nBsubscript𝑛𝐴subscript𝑛𝐵n_{A}=n_{B}, and that the linkage is complete and one-to-one, Chambers, (2009) imposes an “exchangeable” structure on 𝐐𝐐\mathbf{Q}. Formally, the exchangeable linkage error (ELE) model is (Chambers,, 2009)

[𝐐](i∈𝐀,j∈𝐁)=[Pr ​(Δi​j=1|𝐋A​i,𝐋B​j,𝐗B​j)](i∈𝐀,j∈𝐁)={λ, if ​i=j1−λnA−1, if ​i≠j.subscriptdelimited-[]𝐐formulae-sequence𝑖𝐀𝑗𝐁subscriptdelimited-[]Pr subscriptΔ𝑖𝑗conditional1subscript𝐋𝐴𝑖subscript𝐋𝐵𝑗subscript𝐗𝐵𝑗formulae-sequence𝑖𝐀𝑗𝐁cases𝜆 if 𝑖𝑗otherwise1𝜆subscript𝑛𝐴1 if 𝑖𝑗otherwise\displaystyle\begin{split}[\mathbf{Q}]_{(i\in\mathbf{A},j\in\mathbf{B})}&=[\text{Pr }(\Delta_{ij}=1|\mathbf{L}_{Ai},\mathbf{L}_{Bj},\mathbf{X}_{Bj})]_{(i\in\mathbf{A},j\in\mathbf{B})}\\ &=\begin{cases}\lambda,\text{ if }i=j\\ \frac{1-\lambda}{n_{A}-1},\text{ if }i\neq j.\end{cases}\end{split} (14)

This construct implies that (i) every record j∈𝐁𝑗𝐁j\in\mathbf{B} has probability λ𝜆\lambda of being the correct link for record i∈𝐀𝑖𝐀i\in\mathbf{A}, and (ii) any two records that are not linked to i∈𝐀𝑖𝐀i\in\mathbf{A} are equally likely to be the correct links.

Exchangeability implies that the linkage is independent of the linking and substantive variables, so that the linkage mechanism is LCAR. In many applications, this assumption may be overly stringent, as the probability of correct linkage can be heterogeneous across records (Winkler,, 2021). A possible solution is to assume that the linkage probabilities are homogeneous within disjoint subgroups (or blocks) of the linked file, rather than across all the linked records (Chambers and Diniz da Silva,, 2020).

For inference on 𝜷𝜷\boldsymbol{\beta} in Equation (12), Chambers, (2009) proposes different types of weighting matrices υ​(𝐗B;𝜷)𝜐subscript𝐗𝐵𝜷\upsilon(\mathbf{X}_{B};\boldsymbol{\beta}). In the case of linear regression, setting υ​(𝐗B;𝜷)=𝐗B⊤𝜐subscript𝐗𝐵𝜷superscriptsubscript𝐗𝐵top\upsilon(\mathbf{X}_{B};\boldsymbol{\beta})=\mathbf{X}_{B}^{\top} yields an estimator with a ratio-type bias correction, similar in spirit to Scheuren and Winkler, (1993). Setting υ​(𝐗B;𝜷)=𝐗B⊤​𝐐⊤𝜐subscript𝐗𝐵𝜷superscriptsubscript𝐗𝐵topsuperscript𝐐top\upsilon(\mathbf{X}_{B};\boldsymbol{\beta})=\mathbf{X}_{B}^{\top}\mathbf{Q}^{\top}, yields the Lahiri-Larsen estimator, with 𝐐𝐐\mathbf{Q} defined in Equation (14). Setting υ​(𝐗B;𝜷)=𝐗B⊤​𝐐⊤​(σ2​𝐈nA+𝚺)−1𝜐subscript𝐗𝐵𝜷superscriptsubscript𝐗𝐵topsuperscript𝐐topsuperscriptsuperscript𝜎2subscript𝐈subscript𝑛𝐴𝚺1\upsilon(\mathbf{X}_{B};\boldsymbol{\beta})=\mathbf{X}_{B}^{\top}\mathbf{Q}^{\top}(\sigma^{2}\mathbf{I}_{n_{A}}+\mathbf{\Sigma})^{-1}, where σ2=𝕍⁡(𝐘A|𝐗B)superscript𝜎2𝕍conditionalsubscript𝐘𝐴subscript𝐗𝐵\sigma^{2}=\operatorname{\mathbb{V}}(\mathbf{Y}_{A}|\mathbf{X}_{B}) and 𝚺=𝕍⁡(𝚫​𝔼⁡(𝐘A|𝐗B)|𝐗B)𝚺𝕍conditional𝚫𝔼conditionalsubscript𝐘𝐴subscript𝐗𝐵subscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{\Sigma}=\operatorname{\mathbb{V}}(\boldsymbol{\Delta}\operatorname{\mathbb{E}}(\mathbf{Y}_{A}|\mathbf{X}_{B})|\mathbf{X}_{B}), yields the asymptotically efficient best linear unbiased estimator (BLUE) of 𝜷𝜷\boldsymbol{\beta}. Corresponding estimators for the case of logistic regression have also been proposed in Chambers, (2009, pp.22-23). Chambers, (2009) derives Sandwich-type asymptotic sampling variances of these estimators, which account for the variability from using an estimate of λ𝜆\lambda.

Kim and Chambers, 2012a extend Equation (12) to the case of incomplete linkage, when some records from both files may remain unlinked. For valid inference, Kim and Chambers, 2012a assume ignorable non-linkage, which implies that unlinked records in each file are a random sample of all the records in that file. Equivalently, the relationship between 𝐘A∗subscriptsuperscript𝐘𝐴\mathbf{Y}^{*}_{A} and 𝐗Bsubscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{X}_{B} is the same among linked and unlinked records. This assumption is equivalent to unit non-response in surveys occurring completely at random (Rubin,, 1976). When the non-linkage is not ignorable, Kim and Chambers, 2012a propose to adjust regression coefficient estimates using inverse probability weighting (Seaman and White,, 2011).

Zhang and Tuoto, (2021) use the ELE model to develop pseudo-OLS estimators for linear regression, that accommodate incomplete linkage and heterogeneous linkage probabilities. Other extensions of the ELE model include its application to multi-file linkage (Kim and Chambers, 2012b, ; Kim and Chambers,, 2015), to estimation of survey-weighted population totals (Chipperfield,, 2019), to survival analysis (Vo et al.,, 2024), to robust regression in the presence of outliers (Chambers et al.,, 2022), and to estimation using calibrated auxiliary information (Chambers and Diniz da Silva,, 2020). Sensitivity of the linear regression estimators to the ELE assumption has also been demonstrated, theoretically (Zhang and Tuoto,, 2021), and via simulations (Chambers et al.,, 2019).

4 Simulation studies

We examine the performance of selected methods from Sections 2 and 3 using extensive simulations. These methods encompass a wide range of linkage and inference techniques, and depict the main performance trends. We consider two simulation scenarios, corresponding to the primary and secondary analysis settings.

4.1 Scenario 1: Primary analysis

4.1.1 Simulation design

We generate files 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A} and 𝐁𝐁\mathbf{B} of sizes nA=600subscript𝑛𝐴600n_{A}=600 and nB=900subscript𝑛𝐵900n_{B}=900, respectively. The simulations are designed as a factorial experiment with six factors classified into five main categories:

  1. 1.

    Overlap: The overlap represents the proportion of true links. It is defined as the proportion of records from file 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A} that exist in file 𝐁𝐁\mathbf{B}, as a fraction of the smaller file. We examine three levels of the overlap: 100% (complete overlap), 50% (medium overlap), and 20% (low overlap).

  2. 2.

    Blocking: We consider two blocking scenarios. In the first scenario, both files comprise 6 blocks. Consequently, there are 100 records per block in file 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A}, and 150 records per block in file 𝐁𝐁\mathbf{B}. In the second scenario, both files comprise 60 blocks, so that each block in file 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A} contains 10 records, and each block in file 𝐁𝐁\mathbf{B} contains 15 records.

  3. 3.

    Linking variables: We examine the effect of the discriminatory power (DP) of the linking variables under two scenarios. In the high DP scenario, we simulate four linking variables that represent an individual’s zip code stratum (with 30 categories), last name (with nA+nB−nA​Bsubscript𝑛𝐴subscript𝑛𝐵subscript𝑛𝐴𝐵n_{A}+n_{B}-n_{AB} unique values), race (with 5 categories), and year of birth. In the low DP scenario, we simulate four variables to represent individual’s gender (with 2 categories), last name (with nAsubscript𝑛𝐴n_{A} unique values), race (with 5 categories), and year of birth. In both cases, we generate the year of birth and race from the same distributions, but vary how the other linking variables are generated.

  4. 4.

    Variables for post-linkage analysis: For record pairs that are links, we generate 𝐘Asubscript𝐘𝐴\mathbf{Y}_{A} and 𝐗Bsubscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{X}_{B} from a bivariate normal distribution

    (YA​lXB​l)​∼i​i​d​N2​((00),(42​ρ2​ρ1)).matrixsubscript𝑌𝐴𝑙subscript𝑋𝐵𝑙𝑖𝑖𝑑similar-tosubscript𝑁2matrix00matrix42𝜌2𝜌1\displaystyle\begin{pmatrix}Y_{Al}\\ X_{Bl}\end{pmatrix}\overset{iid}{\sim}N_{2}\left(\begin{pmatrix}0\\ 0\end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix}4&2\rho\\ 2\rho&1\end{pmatrix}\right). (15)

    Under this setup, a linear regression of 𝐘Asubscript𝐘𝐴\mathbf{Y}_{A} on 𝐗Bsubscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{X}_{B} is of the form YA​l=β​XB​l+ϵlsubscript𝑌𝐴𝑙𝛽subscript𝑋𝐵𝑙subscriptitalic-ϵ𝑙{Y}_{Al}=\beta X_{Bl}+\epsilon_{l}, where β=2​ρ𝛽2𝜌\beta=2\rho, and ϵl​∼i​i​d​N​(0,4​(1−ρ2))subscriptitalic-ϵ𝑙𝑖𝑖𝑑similar-to𝑁041superscript𝜌2\epsilon_{l}\overset{iid}{\sim}N(0,4(1-\rho^{2})).     Measurement error: We induce measurement errors in two out of the four linking variables: the last name and the year of birth. We vary the level and the mechanism of error generation.

    1. (a)

      Error level: We consider two error levels: 10% (low) and 40% (high).

    2. (b)

      Error mechanism: Within the high and low error levels, we generate measurement errors according to the LCAR, SNL, NL, WNL, and IL mechanisms. Under LCAR, we randomly select records from the two files and introduce errors in the last name and the year of birth. Under SNL, we let the probability of error in a record to depend on an individual’s race. Under NL and WNL, we let the probability of error in a record depend on 𝐗Bsubscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{X}_{B}, and 𝐘Asubscript𝐘𝐴\mathbf{Y}_{A}, respectively. Under IL, this probability depends on an unobserved variable which is associated with 𝐘Asubscript𝐘𝐴\mathbf{Y}_{A} and 𝐗Bsubscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{X}_{B}.

In summary, we generate 24×3×5=240superscript24352402^{4}\times 3\times 5=240 simulation configurations. For each configuration, we generate 100 simulation replications. We describe the data generation process in the supplementary materials.

4.1.2 Evaluation metrics

We evaluate the performance of seven methods when estimating the regression slope, β𝛽\beta. For each method, in each simulation replication, we record the point estimate β^^𝛽\hat{\beta}, its estimated variance, and whether a 95% interval estimate covers the true value of β𝛽\beta. We summarize the results across all replications by calculating the mean bias of the point estimate, the average estimated standard error (SE), and the coverage rate of the 95% interval estimate.

4.1.3 Record linkage and inference methods

We link files 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A} and 𝐁𝐁\mathbf{B} using the FS method, implemented in the fastlink package (Enamorado et al.,, 2019) in R. Using the linked file, we obtain an estimate of the slope, β^^𝛽\hat{\beta}, its sampling variance, and a 95% confidence interval for β𝛽\beta.

We implement the weighted estimated equations approach of Han and Lahiri, (2019) in the complete overlap scenario. We estimate the matrix of posterior matching probabilities, 𝐐^^𝐐\mathbf{\hat{Q}}, using the fastLink package in R. We consider three versions of the matrix 𝐐^^𝐐\mathbf{\hat{Q}}: (i) the full matrix without any modifications (HLF); (ii) in every row, we set all entries except the two highest to zero (HL2); and (iii) in every row, we set all entries except the highest to zero (HL1). We obtain the estimate β^^𝛽\hat{\beta} using the blocked version of Equation (12) (Han and Lahiri,, 2019, p.5). To estimate the sampling error of β^^𝛽\hat{\beta}, we follow the jacknife resampling approach in Han and Lahiri, (2019). In each iteration of the jacknife, we leave out records from a block in both files, so that the number of jacknife replicates is equal to the number of blocks. We aggregate results across all jacknife replicates to obtain the sampling variance of β^^𝛽\hat{\beta}, and a 95% confidence interval for β𝛽\beta.

We also examine the pseudo-likelihood method of Hof and Zwinderman, (2012) (abbreviated as HZ). To construct the pseudo-likelihood for the distribution of 𝐘Asubscript𝐘𝐴\mathbf{Y}_{A} given 𝐗Bsubscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{X}_{B}, we use Equation (8) from Hof and Zwinderman, (2012, p.79). We calculate the probabilities for the observed agreement patterns using the fastLink package in R. We obtain the point estimate β^^𝛽\hat{\beta} using the EM algorithm (Hof and Zwinderman,, 2012, Appendix B). To compute the sampling variance of β^^𝛽\hat{\beta}, we invert the observed Fisher information matrix (Hof and Zwinderman,, 2012, p.80). We compute a 95% confidence interval for β𝛽\beta under asymptotic normality of the sampling distribution of β^^𝛽\hat{\beta}.

We use four Bayesian methods to link files 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A} and 𝐁𝐁\mathbf{B}, and estimate the slope β𝛽\beta. The first method is that of Sadinle, (2017) (abbreviated as SL), which we apply independently within each block. We assume a uniform prior distribution over the parameters of the record linkage likelihood in Equation (8). We use exact agreement to compare the zip stratum, gender, race, and the year of birth. We model the similarity in the last names using the Levenshtein edit (L​D)𝐿𝐷(LD) distance (Levenshtein,, 1966). We standardize the L​D𝐿𝐷LD distance to obtain a final measure in the range of [0,1]01[0,1], where 0 represents total agreement and 1 represents total disagreement. Following Sadinle, (2017), we categorize L​D𝐿𝐷LD into four levels of disagreement: perfect agreement (L​D𝐿𝐷LD = 0), mild disagreement (0<L​D≤0.250𝐿𝐷0.250<LD\leq 0.25), low disagreement (0.25<L​D≤0.50.25𝐿𝐷0.50.25<LD\leq 0.5), and extreme disagreement (L​D≥0.5𝐿𝐷0.5LD\geq 0.5). We generate 100010001000 samples from the posterior distribution of the linkage structure, using a Gibbs sampler implemented in the R package BRL (Sadinle,, 2020).

The second Bayesian method is that of Steorts, (2015) (abbreviated as ST), which we apply independently within each block. To implement the linking algorithm, we concatenate records from each block in the two files into a single file, and perform deduplication on the concatenated file. In the record linkage model, we assume that the year of birth, zip stratum, race, and gender are categorical variables, and use the L​D𝐿𝐷LD distance to model similarities on the last name. We set prior distributions and hyperparameters following the recommendations in Steorts, (2015, pp.9-17). We provide specific details of the hyperparameter values in the supplementary materials. We generate 1000 samples from the posterior distribution of the linkage structure, using the Gibbs sampler implemented in the R package blink (Steorts,, 2020).

The third Bayesian method is that of Kamat et al., (2023) (abbreviated as KSG), which augments the likelihood in Equation (8) with associations between 𝐘Asubscript𝐘𝐴\mathbf{Y}_{A} and 𝐗Bsubscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{X}_{B}. For record pair (i,j)𝑖𝑗(i,j), we assume YA​i|XB​j∼N​(β0​M+β1​M​XB​j,σM2)similar-toconditionalsubscript𝑌𝐴𝑖subscript𝑋𝐵𝑗𝑁subscript𝛽0𝑀subscript𝛽1𝑀subscript𝑋𝐵𝑗superscriptsubscript𝜎𝑀2Y_{Ai}|X_{Bj}\sim N(\beta_{0M}+\beta_{1M}X_{Bj},\sigma_{M}^{2}) if the pair is a link, and YA​i|XB​j∼N​(β0​U+β1​U​XB​j,σU2)similar-toconditionalsubscript𝑌𝐴𝑖subscript𝑋𝐵𝑗𝑁subscript𝛽0𝑈subscript𝛽1𝑈subscript𝑋𝐵𝑗superscriptsubscript𝜎𝑈2Y_{Ai}|X_{Bj}\sim N(\beta_{0U}+\beta_{1U}X_{Bj},\sigma_{U}^{2}) if the pair is a non-link. As in the SL algorithm, we assume uniform prior distributions on the parameters defining the similarity on the zip stratum, gender, race, year of birth and last name. To complete the Bayesian model, we assume the improper prior distributions p​(𝜷M,σM)∝σM−2proportional-to𝑝subscript𝜷𝑀subscript𝜎𝑀superscriptsubscript𝜎𝑀2p(\boldsymbol{\beta}_{M},\sigma_{M})\propto\sigma_{M}^{-2} and p​(𝜷U,σU)∝σU−2proportional-to𝑝subscript𝜷𝑈subscript𝜎𝑈superscriptsubscript𝜎𝑈2p(\boldsymbol{\beta}_{U},\sigma_{U})\propto\sigma_{U}^{-2}. We adjust for blocking following the method described in Kamat et al., (2023). We generate 1000 samples from the posterior distribution of the linkage structure using the DA algorithm.

The fourth Bayesian method is that of Gutman et al., (2013) (abbreviated as GT). We apply this method in the complete overlap scenario only. We extend the likelihood in Gutman et al., (2013) to account for associations between variables common to both the files. We model the agreements on the year of birth, zip stratum, race, and gender as Bernoulli random variables. We specify Beta(1,1) prior distributions on the parameters of the Bernoulli distribution. In addition, we model the number of record pairs with LD distances in the ranges (0,0.25)00.25(0,0.25), (0.25,0.5)0.250.5(0.25,0.5), and (0.5,1)0.51(0.5,1) using a multinomial distribution with three parameters. We specify a Dirichlet (1,1,1) prior on each of the parameters. We describe the complete model specification in the supplementary materials. We generate 1000 samples from the posterior distribution of the linkage structure, using the DA algorithm in Gutman et al., (2013). In each DA iteration, we perform 50,0005000050,000 record-pair-switches per block.

For all Bayesian methods, in each posterior sample of the linkage structure, we compute the estimated regression coefficient β^^𝛽\hat{\beta} among the identified links, and its sampling variance. We obtain point and interval estimates across all posterior samples using the MI combining rules described in Section 2.2.

4.1.4 Results

Within each level of the overlap, we identify three simulation factors that have the largest effect on the bias, SE, and coverage, using ANOVA (Cangul et al.,, 2009). The error mechanism, error level, and the discriminatory power are generally the most influential factors across the different evaluation metrics. We report results by averaging over levels of the remaining factors (the block size and the SNR).

Table 1 summarizes the performance for the complete overlap configuration, when the linking variables have high discriminatory power, and there is low measurement error. Across all linkage mechanisms, the bias of β^^𝛽\hat{\beta} is generally negative, as false links attenuate the estimates towards zero. The FS estimator of β𝛽\beta underestimates the true value, and has coverage below the nominal. When the mechanism is LCAR, SNL, or NL, the Bayesian, weighting, and likelihood-based methods have generally small biases. For these linkage mechanisms, the Bayesian methods have the smallest biases, with SL being the most efficient. Moreover, their interval estimates have coverages at or above the nominal. Weighting methods have relatively larger biases, but produce interval estimates with near-nominal coverage. Across the LCAR, SNL, and NL mechanisms, HZ exhibits small biases, but also has the largest SEs among all methods, which results in coverage rates well above 95%.

The bias under all the methods increases when the linkage mechanism is either WNL or IL. Under WNL, GT, KSG, and HL1 produce estimates with relatively smaller bias, but have coverage rates below the nominal. Estimates under HZ have high bias, but inflated SEs result coverage probabilities above the nominal. Under IL, the bias under all the methods increases considerably. The coverage is below-nominal across all the Bayesian methods. The weighting methods have coverage near 88%, while HZ has above-nominal coverage.

Increasing the measurement error has a noticeable impact on the performance of all the methods. When the linking variables are highly discriminatory, increase in the error level leads to larger biases under HZ and the weighting methods (Table S1 in the supplementary materials). In spite of the increased error, the Bayesian methods have relatively small biases under LCAR, SNL, and NL. Under WNL and IL, there is a substantial decrease in performance across all the methods. Under these linkage mechanisms, HZ provides valid coverage at the cost of higher SEs, and ST has the lowest coverage. The results are qualitatively similar when the discriminatory power is low (Tables S2, S3 in the supplementary materials).

Table S5 depicts the results under the medium and low overlap scenarios, when the linking variables have high discriminatory power, and there is low measurement error. Under LCAR, SNL, and NL, estimates under ST have the lowest bias, near-nominal coverage rates, and are the most efficient. Estimates under HZ also have low bias and valid coverage, but with larger standard errors compared to ST. The performance of SL and KSG declines when the overlap is not complete, with KSG offering lower biases and better coverage rates than SL. Under WNL and IL, estimates under ST have larger biases, and below-nominal coverage. Under the medium overlap scenario, KSG and HZ have relatively low biases, with KSG exhibiting smaller SEs, but below-nominal coverage. The relative performance of the methods remains qualitatively unchanged when the error level increases (Table S4), or when the linking variables have low discriminatory power (Tables S5, S6).

However, the estimated SEs are lower, leading to reduced coverage rates.

4.2 Example: Model-based clustering with linked data

We illustrate the use of MI with linked data, when the downstream analysis involves complex modeling. We consider files 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A} and 𝐁𝐁\mathbf{B}, comprising nA=nB=600subscript𝑛𝐴subscript𝑛𝐵600n_{A}=n_{B}=600 records, with complete overlap. For record i𝑖i in both files, we generate a random vector from a mixture of four-dimensional Normal distributions. For mixture component c∈{1,…,4}𝑐1…4c\in\{1,\dots,4\}, let (YA​1​i,YA​2​i,XB​1​i,XB​2​i)(c)′∼N4​(c​𝐮c,c​𝚺c)(Y_{A1i},Y_{A2i},X_{B1i},X_{B2i})^{{}^{\prime}(c)}\sim N_{4}(c\mathbf{u}_{c},c\mathbf{\Sigma}_{c}), where ucsubscript𝑢𝑐u_{c} is a unit vector with 1 at the ct​hsuperscript𝑐𝑡ℎc^{th} position, and 0 elsewhere, and 𝚺c=(0.50.10.10.10.10.50.10.10.10.10.50.10.10.10.10.5)subscript𝚺𝑐0.50.10.10.10.10.50.10.10.10.10.50.10.10.10.10.5\mathbf{\Sigma}_{c}=\bigg{(}\begin{smallmatrix}0.5&0.1&0.1&0.1\\ 0.1&0.5&0.1&0.1\\ 0.1&0.1&0.5&0.1\\ 0.1&0.1&0.1&0.5\end{smallmatrix}\bigg{)}. The proportions of records assigned to the four clusters are {0.4,0.3,0.2,0.1}0.40.30.20.1\{0.4,0.3,0.2,0.1\}. This design ensures that the clusters are relatively well-separated (Lee and Harel,, 2022). We assign the variables 𝐘A​1subscript𝐘𝐴1\mathbf{Y}_{A1} and 𝐘A​2subscript𝐘𝐴2\mathbf{Y}_{A2} to file 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A}, and 𝐗B​1subscript𝐗𝐵1\mathbf{X}_{B1} and 𝐗B​2subscript𝐗𝐵2\mathbf{X}_{B2} to file 𝐁𝐁\mathbf{B}. The goal of the analysis is to estimate (i) the population mean vector; and (ii) the correlation between 𝐘A​1subscript𝐘𝐴1\mathbf{Y}_{A1} and 𝐗B​1subscript𝐗𝐵1\mathbf{X}_{B1} within each cluster, after the files have been linked.

We let both files comprise three linking variables drawn from a discrete uniform distribution over 5, 10, and 20 categories, respectively. We link the two files using the SL algorithm, using binary agreement to construct comparison vectors. Within each posterior sample of the linkage structure, we fit a four-component Gaussian mixture model via the EM algorithm implemented in the mclust package (Scrucca et al.,, 2016) in R. We estimate the cluster means and correlations within each posterior sample of the linkage structure, and combine these estimates using the MI combining rules from Section 2.2. Table 3 depicts the results across 1000 posterior samples. The imputation procedure recovers the true cluster means, correlations, and mixing proportions with reasonable accuracy.

In this example, the mixture components can be recovered well, as all components are well-separated. In more complex scenarios, label-invariance of the mixture model may require restrictions on the ordering of the cluster means. This issue is also relevant to other multivariate techniques like factor analysis (Nassiri et al.,, 2018), where factor loadings may change order across posterior samples of the linkage structure. With added computation, fully Bayesian estimation can also be performed using a version of the DA algorithm. As the weighting methods are restricted to generalized linear models, they cannot be directly applied to this example.

4.3 Scenario 2: Secondary analysis

4.3.1 Simulation design

In this scenario, we generate a linked file of size nA​B=600subscript𝑛𝐴𝐵600n_{AB}=600. For record l𝑙l in the linked file, we generate (YA​l,XB​l)subscript𝑌𝐴𝑙subscript𝑋𝐵𝑙(Y_{Al},X_{Bl}) based on Equation (15). We examine two levels of ρ𝜌\rho: ρ=0.9𝜌0.9\rho=0.9 (high SNR) and ρ=0.4𝜌0.4\rho=0.4 (low SNR).

The nA​Bsubscript𝑛𝐴𝐵n_{AB} linked records are partitioned into three blocks of sizes n1=100subscript𝑛1100n_{1}=100, n2=200subscript𝑛2200n_{2}=200, and n3=300subscript𝑛3300n_{3}=300. Following Chambers, (2009), we constrain the linkage errors to be within blocks. In the low linkage error scenario, we let the error rates within the three blocks to be {5%,10%,15%}percent5percent10percent15\{5\%,10\%,15\%\}. In the high linkage error scenario, we let the error rates to be {15%,20%,25%}percent15percent20percent25\{15\%,20\%,25\%\}. We consider four mechanisms for generating the linkage errors: (i) the LCAR/ELE mechanism; (ii) the NL mechanism; (iii) the WNL mechanism, and (iv) the IL mechanism, where the linkage errors depend on an unobserved variable associated with 𝐘A​ and ​𝐗Bsubscript𝐘𝐴 and subscript𝐗𝐵\mathbf{Y}_{A}\text{ and }\mathbf{X}_{B}. Under each mechanism, we generate errors by shuffling the values of the outcome 𝐘Asubscript𝐘𝐴\mathbf{Y}_{A}. We provide a detailed description of the data generation process in the supplementary materials.

In summary, we generate 24=16superscript24162^{4}=16 simulation configurations, which are implemented as a full factorial design. In each configuration, we generate 100 simulation replications.

4.3.2 Inference methods

We compare five methods for inference on β𝛽\beta, the slope of the regression of YAsubscript𝑌𝐴Y_{A} on XBsubscript𝑋𝐵X_{B}. We first consider the naive estimator of β𝛽\beta, that does not account for possible linkage errors. The second inferential method is the weighted estimating equations approach of Chambers, (2009). We consider three weighting estimators: the bias-adjusted ratio type estimator (ChR), the Lahiri-Larsen estimator under the ELE assumption (ChL), and the BLUE (ChB). These estimators require an estimate of the probability of correct linkage per block, λ^b,b=1,2,3formulae-sequencesubscript^𝜆𝑏𝑏123\hat{\lambda}_{b},b=1,2,3. To obtain λ^bsubscript^𝜆𝑏\hat{\lambda}_{b}, we use a random audit sample of size nb/2subscript𝑛𝑏2n_{b}/2 in block b𝑏b, and record the proportion of correct links nb​csubscript𝑛𝑏𝑐n_{bc}. We set λ^b=min⁡{nb−1​(nb−1),max⁡{nb−1,nb​c}}subscript^𝜆𝑏superscriptsubscript𝑛𝑏1subscript𝑛𝑏1superscriptsubscript𝑛𝑏1subscript𝑛𝑏𝑐\hat{\lambda}_{b}=\min\{n_{b}^{-1}(n_{b}-1),\max\{n_{b}^{-1},n_{bc}\}\}. This method avoids overly optimistic estimates of λbsubscript𝜆𝑏\lambda_{b} when it is close to one (Chambers,, 2009). We compute standard errors for each estimator using the Sandwich variance formulae in Chambers, (2009, pp.13-17).

The third inferential method is that of Gutman et al., (2016) (abbreviated as GT). We fit a mixture of linear regressions independently within each block. We assume diffuse proper prior distributions on the regression model parameters and the mixture class probabilities. We generate 100010001000 samples from the posterior distribution of the mixture model parameters, using the DA algorithm. In each posterior sample, we estimate β𝛽\beta, and its sampling variance among record pairs classified as links. We compute point and interval estimates using MI (Section 2.2).

We also examine the likelihood-based method of Slawski et al., (2021) (abbreviated as SLW). Under this method, we fit a two-class mixture model using the EM algorithm, and obtain an estimate β^^𝛽\hat{\beta} as described in Slawski et al., (2021, pp. 996-997). We compute the covariance matrix as described in Appendix C of Slawski et al., (2021). We obtain confidence intervals for β𝛽\beta under an asymptotic normal approximation for the sampling distribution of β^^𝛽\hat{\beta}.

We summarize results across all simulation replications in terms of the mean bias, the average estimated standard error (SE), and the coverage rate of the 95% interval estimate.

4.3.3 Results

Table S11 depicts the results when the linkage error levels are low, and the SNR is high. The naive estimator underestimates β𝛽\beta across all the linkage mechanisms, and has below-nominal coverage. All the other estimation methods reduce the linkage error bias. Under the ELE mechanism, all methods (except the naive) yield estimates with a small bias and above-nominal coverage, with GT and SLW having the smallest SEs. Under the NL mechanism, all methods yield coverage rates close to 95%, with SLW being the most efficient.

The bias under all methods increases when the linkage mechanism is WNL. The increased bias leads to interval estimates with coverages close to 70% for ChR, ChL, and 50% for ChB. GT and SLW have smaller biases and SEs, with coverage rates of 77% and 73%, respectively. The decrease in performance is more apparent under IL, where ChR, ChL, and ChB have biases that are larger than the naive estimator. The biases and SEs under GT and SLW are lower than the weighting methods, but coverage is below the nominal.

Table S9 in the supplementary materials displays the results when the linkage error level and the SNR are low. Across all the linkage mechanisms, the naive estimator continues to show large negative biases, with coverage rates below the nominal. Under the ELE mechanism, the weighting methods have low biases with coverage rates near 95%. Biases under the weighting methods increase under the NL, WNL, and IL mechanisms, with coverage rates near 95% under NL, and near 85% under WNL and IL. Across all linkage mechanisms, the performance of the weighting methods is better when the SNR is low compared to when it is high. Evidently, the linkage mechanism has a less noticeable impact on the inferences when the association between YA​ and ​XBsubscript𝑌𝐴 and subscript𝑋𝐵Y_{A}\text{ and }X_{B} is low. Under all linkage mechanisms, the bias under GT and SLW is higher compared to the high SNR scenario. This is because both models rely on the association between YA​ and ​XBsubscript𝑌𝐴 and subscript𝑋𝐵Y_{A}\text{ and }X_{B}, which is attenuated in this scenario. Nonetheless, the coverage under GT and SLW is close to nominal.

Table S10 in the supplementary materials depicts the results when the error level is high and the SNR is high. Due to the higher error level, biases under all the methods increase, especially under the WNL and IL mechanisms. The weighting methods show the highest increase in bias, with coverage near 57% under WNL, and 3% under IL. SLW has the smallest bias across all the linkage mechanisms. GT and SLW have coverages near the nominal under the ELE and NL mechanisms, but close to 50% when the linkage mechanism is WNL or IL. For the same error level, the relative performance of the methods is qualitatively similar when the SNR is low (Table S11).

5 Concluding remarks

In this article, we review inferential methods with linked data files. Following the missing data literature, we group these methods into three categories: likelihood and Bayesian methods, imputation methods, and weighting methods. We outline the assumptions underlying the methods, and discuss their possible benefits and shortcomings.

Using simulations, we evaluate the performance of selected methods for primary and secondary analysis of linked files. In the primary analysis setting, our simulations identify two factors that significantly affect performance: the amount of overlap between the files, and the linkage mechanism. With high overlap, and under LCAR, SNL, or NL, all methods yield generally valid inferences. Under these linkage mechanisms, the model of Steorts, (2015) holds up well with decreasing levels of overlap. Under WNL, the joint modeling approaches from Section 2.1.2 offer some advantages over the other methods. When the linkage mechanism is IL, there is a noticeable decline in performance across most of the methods. The linkage mechanism also has a considerable impact on inferences in the secondary analysis setting.

We conclude by pointing out some important and open avenues for research. First, the area of post-linkage analysis has remained generally underdeveloped beyond generalized linear models. In Section 4.2, we provide an illustrative example of applying MI to cluster analysis with linked files. However, other multivariate analysis techniques call for more sophisticated methodological developments. Second, as indicated in the simulations, linkage mechanisms can heavily influence post-linkage inferences. These mechanisms underpin every record linkage algorithm, and are untestable in practice. Thus, it is crucial to assess the sensitivity of inferences to alternative linkage mechanisms than those assumed in the linkage process. As there are parallels between the linkage and missing data mechanisms, sensitivity analysis methods for record linkage can borrow from the rich missing data literature. Finally, as demonstrated in the article, MI offers an appealing alternative to fully Bayesian inference with linked data. However, the validity of MI inferences under more elaborate scenarios, for example, with multiple analysis models and uncongeniality, are unstudied.

3 Details of simulation studies

In this section, we describe the setup and implementation of the simulation studies in the main text.

3.1 Scenario 1: Primary analysis

We generate files 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A} and 𝐁𝐁\mathbf{B} of sizes nA=600subscript𝑛𝐴600n_{A}=600 and nB=900subscript𝑛𝐵900n_{B}=900, respectively. The number of true links nA​Bsubscript𝑛𝐴𝐵n_{AB} is determined by the overlap between the two files. For true links, we generate the linking variables in file 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A}, and replicate their values in file 𝐁𝐁\mathbf{B}. For the non-linking record pairs, linking variables in both files are generated independently.

3.1.1 Data generation

Linking variables in the high discriminatory power setting:

In this setting, we generate four linking variables to represent an individual’s zip stratum, year of birth, race, and last name. We generate the zip stratum for each record from a discrete uniform distribution over {1,…,30}1…30\{1,\dots,30\}. We generate the year of birth by simulating age from a normal distribution, N​(30,102)𝑁30superscript102N(30,10^{2}), and converting it to the year of birth. Specifically, for record r𝑟r, we generate the age ar​∼i​i​d​N​(30,102)subscript𝑎𝑟𝑖𝑖𝑑similar-to𝑁30superscript102a_{r}\overset{iid}{\sim}N(30,10^{2}),and compute the year of birth as Y​O​Br=2025−ar𝑌𝑂subscript𝐵𝑟2025subscript𝑎𝑟YOB_{r}=2025-a_{r}. For every record, we generate the race from a discrete uniform distribution over {1,…,5}1…5\{1,\dots,5\}. To generate last names, we use the randomNames package in R, and generate nA+nB−nA​Bsubscript𝑛𝐴subscript𝑛𝐵subscript𝑛𝐴𝐵n_{A}+n_{B}-n_{AB} unique last names (so that every record has a unique last name).

Linking variables in the low discriminatory power setting:

In this setting, we generate four linking variables to represent an individual’s gender, year of birth, race, and last name. We generate gender for each record from a discrete uniform distribution over {1,2}12\{1,2\}. We generate the year of birth and race in the same manner as in the high discriminatory power setting. We generate a set of last names using the randomNames package, with the number of unique values set to nAsubscript𝑛𝐴n_{A}. We assign a last name to every record by sampling with replacement from this set.

3.1.2 Implementation of record linkage algorithms

Parameters in the Steorts, (2015) model:

The entity resolution model of Steorts, (2015) entails specification of four parameters: (i) the maximum number of latent population entities; (ii) a “steepness” parameter, that governs how likely it is for a string field to be distorted to values that are far from the latent entity’s value; and (iii) two hyperparameters (b1,b2)subscript𝑏1subscript𝑏2(b_{1},b_{2}) of the Beta prior on the probability that a record in a file is distorted on the kt​hsuperscript𝑘𝑡ℎk^{th} linking variable. We set the maximum number of latent entities to be the total sample size of the concatenated, block-level file. Following Steorts, (2015), we set the steepness parameter equal to 1. We set the hyperparameters b1=1subscript𝑏11b_{1}=1 and b2=99subscript𝑏299b_{2}=99, so that the prior in (iii) has a small mean, and is reasonably diffuse (Steorts,, 2015).
